				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">First off, if you don't have luclin get it or this won't be any help <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Well, I was reading through some strategies and thought to add one of my own.  First off, the subject is only part of this strategy.  This is largely for those that do not want to ruin katta faction this early on, although it is nice by itself.  If you don't mind ruining the faction Katta is a great place if your guards aren't already taken.  But Mons Letalis... its almost always empty on E'ci atleast.  They are especially nice from 47 to about 50 (I killed lower level katta guards until occassional light blue at around that time).
<br />

<br />
To get to Mons Letalis go to Nexus and then to Netherbian Lair, run till you hit the pillar and turn right towards Marus Seru.  From there you go north and to the west of the recuso camp in the corner is your zone to Mons Letalis.
<br />

<br />
I would try to keep kei at all times if you want to take out the entire first room counting walkers, run to nexus and then gate back (bind yourself near zone from Maru Seru inside that little tunnel), I prefer to be bound where I hunt and run for kei because I have that little extra time for kei to last longer.
<br />

<br />
First off, let me tell you that if you want to travel in Mons Letalis safely I would not recommend hunting the Shik'nar because they are all over the place and there are alot better things to hunt.  Namely Thought Leeches!  Using these weak monsters you can easily rake in a level in about 4 hours with kei if you know what your doing, and that's pretty nice in my book since its practically a sure thing when it comes to getting the camp.
<br />

<br />
The most important thing to know about the Thought Leeches:  NORMAL THOUGHT LEECHES ARE WEAK!!!  I mean WEAK, they hit for like 80s which is very nice, the only problem is they do seem to hit slightly faster than most mobs their level.  But for mages they are cake.  Various "special" Leeches can range from doing 80s to about 112 damage but are not very common (I saw maybe 1 every hour on average).  They drop parts for various classes' Twilight Sea Quests (specials only of course), research items, other quest items (some very nice wisdom shield but rather involved quest), as well as around 5-6pp max.
<br />

<br />
Where to pull:  Last bend in the tunnel before the room along wall.  You'll be able to see into the room from there although not all of it.  It is not exactly a "safe spot" since the wandering mob in the entrance tunnel will sometimes agro you if you aren't far enough over but read further and I'll explain why that won't matter unless you go afk (which you don't).
<br />

<br />
The danger of the leech caves (especially at entrance) is the wandering leeches that can get rather annoying if you aren't careful.  Most important thing to do is to watch the wanderer's pathing first off, as a mage I would use my clay bracelet for its eye of zomm to explore the room.  In the tunnel between outside of the cave and to the first room houses one walking leech that travels almost the entire length of the tunnel.  Kill him first since he is in your way, and the fact he is one of the few adds I would ever get if things took longer than usual.
<br />

<br />
Secondly, right at the end of the tunnel beside the room entrance is a leech hiding behind the rock on right part of the wall (you can't see him, but he'll agro you if you get close).  That is exactly how you pull him, so make sure you to look for wanderers (you will see them easily if they are there, they walk right past you) before agroing him.
<br />

<br />
Then there are 3 more static leeches in the room that I was always able to single pull unless I was stupid (didn't come till like 47-48 though).  There are also like 2 wandering mobs that will walk back and forth but you have several minutes between them showing themselves in the room.
<br />

<br />
With static spawns I would go front left, back left, and then one on right side behind the large pillar that splits the room.  I believe my focused 44 earth pet full buffed (with damage shield of course, big help) was best at this point to keep from walking.  And as long as you pull to the first bend they'll ALWAYS walk towards the exit of the tunnel (this is where the walker in tunnel usually is most annoying and why I used earth pet).
<br />

<br />
At 49 I used new focused earth pet and fully buffed it could easily solo one of the leeches and could often take two right after each other without needing to be healed, and if you manage to mess up with an add you can either act as healer or learn how to chain fight more than one mob and sometimes not necessary if you seperate the two well enough, but it is close quarters <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" />  LEARN HOW TO DO THIS if you don't already know, it can be the difference between you being dead, having to gate, or getting experience from them both (or more if you are fighting low dark blues, helped me couple times with bad pulls in BW at hornet nest at 51) <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" />  killed 2 cinder and an ember hornet using this tactic.
<br />

<br />
Okay, the spawntime is only 12 minutes and in that time you could kill all 7 leeches (around 1% a kill or more I believe at 49).  With kei I couldn't quite med to full between full respawns (255int and aroundd 400 extra mana).  If you have horse or staff (or epic for those very very few uber mages with uber friends) would be alot easier <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Like I said... if you're careful and willing to take the risk while learning its very very worth it.  At about 50 they tend to become light blue if I remember correctly although it might not be till 51, can't remember <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Think I died only twice in the time I was there but first time was because I was still rather new at it and second was because I was stupid.  If you want to stay in Mons Letalis longer you can, but after most leeches go lt blue at around 50-51 I would recommend heading out into the open areas.  As long as you aren't KoS to Shik'nar (hatchlings are not the same, they were kos to me even though the others were not) the only thing that would agro me were stonegrabbers which just so happened to be summoned!  (Equip pet with swords and fun but annoying trying to hunt them down throughout zone which is why I originally came to Mons for).
<br />

<br />
A problem hunting Stonegrabbers is that the Rockhoppers will help them out even though they aren't kos otherwise.  And some of those rockhoppers can be nasty.  If you want to hunt stonegrabbers and rockhoppers at higher levels (can stay till like low mid 50s I believe) head to north part of zone near the Grey.  They seem to be more common around there, especially around north western corner hidden inside of the crevices that wind throughout the zone.
<br />

<br />
If you die getting a rez is almost out of the question unless you find a cleric willing to come to you, but since you can regain the experience in about 20 minutes (upto 50) or less it isn't TOO big of deal <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Hopefully this will be of help to some mages out there that are tired of the more populated and overcamped hunting spots.  I would recommend hunting elsewhere post leeches unless you want to chance rockhopper pelts which usually sell rather nicely to tailors.  Their levels vary considerably depending on type but most mature rockhoppers still give decent experience for my 54 mage and even my 55 druid can get some dark blues here... track helps at that level though hehe.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
